<?  include '../style.php';?><table border=1><tr><th></th><th>Composer name</th><th>Group</th><th>Short description</th></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>FRA</b> 1100-1200<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=208'>Perotin<br><td bgcolor=white >Notre Dame school<br><td bgcolor=white >Polyphony, ars antiqua. Organum.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>FRA</b> 1300-1377<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=173'>Machaut, Guillaume de<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Ars nova. Secular and sacred vocal music. Not smooth melodically and rhythmically, independent voices, melodic interest in upper voices, little use of thirds, cadences are clear cut/no overlap; cadences focus on perfect consonances<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>FRA</b> 1400-1474<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=90'>Dufay, Guillaume<br><td bgcolor=white >Burgundian School<br><td bgcolor=white >Late-medieval polyphonic structural techniques.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>ITA</b> 1525-1594<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=204'>Palestrina, Giovanni Pierluigi da<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Roman School<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Sacred vocal music. Smooth melodically and rhythmically, treats all voice parts equally (mostly imitative counterpoint with harmony based on thirds, with careful control of dissonances as passing tines/neighbor notes, suspensions; cadences are overlapping and focused on full triads)<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>FLM</b> 1532-1594<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=163'>Lassus, Orlande de<br><td bgcolor=white >Franco-Flemish School V<br><td bgcolor=white >Motets, Italian madrigals, villanellas, French chansons, German lieder.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ENG</b> 1543-1623<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=48'>Byrd, William<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Sacred and secular polyphony, keyboard (the so-called Virginalist school), and consort music.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ITA</b> 1554-1612<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=107'>Gabrieli, Giovanni<br><td bgcolor=white >Venetian School<br><td bgcolor=white >Shift from Renaissance to Baroque idioms. <br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ITA</b> 1561-1613<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=110'>Gesualdo, Carlo<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Murderer. Wildly chromatic. Most experimental and expressive.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ENG</b> 1563-1626<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=89'>Dowland, John<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Melancholy songs.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>ITA</b> 1567-1643<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=189'>Monteverdi, Claudio<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Venetian School<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Innovative vocal.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>DEU</b> 1571-1621<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=214'>Praetorius, Michael<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Protestant hymns.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ENG</b> 1583-1625<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=111'>Gibbons, Orlando<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Complete mastery of counterpoint and wonderful gift for melody.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>DEU</b> 1585-1672<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=248'>Schutz, Heinrich<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Harmonies often result from the contrapuntal alignment of voices rather than from any sense of "harmonic motion"; contrastingly, much of his music shows a strong tonal pull when approaching cadences<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>FRA</b> 1626-1661<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=71'>Couperin, Louis<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Harpsichord master.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>FRA</b> 1632-1687<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=170'>Lully, Jean-Baptiste<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Power. Live when fast, deep when sad. First french opera.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>DNK/DEU</b> 1637-1707<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=47'>Buxtehude, Dietrich<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Organ. Influenced Bach.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>DEU</b> 1653-1706<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=201'>Pachelbel, Johann<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Canon<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>FRA</b> 1668-1733<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=70'>Couperin, Francois<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Extensive coloratura<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ITA</b> 1671-1751<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=4'>Albinoni, Tomaso Giovanni<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Instrumental<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>ITA</b> 1678-1741<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=287'>Vivaldi, Antonio<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Most predictable, eldritch, popular, flamboyantly exuberant. Diligent violin teacher.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>DEU</b> 1681-1767<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=277'>Telemann, Georg Philipp<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Calm, measured<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>FRA</b> 1683-1764<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=220'>Rameau, Jean-Philippe<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Revolutionary harmonies after Lully. More courtly.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>DEU</b> 1685-1750<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=12'>Bach, Johann Sebastian<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Counterpoint, god, infinite line, winter, cold, serious, spiritual, cosmic, global<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>DEU/ENG</b> 1685-1759<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=133'>Handel, George Frideric<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Summer, warm, happy, courtier, diverse. Opera has contemporary sound.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ITA</b> 1692-1770<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=274'>Tartini, Giuseppe<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Violin virtuoso<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ENG</b> 1710-1778<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=7'>Arne, Thomas<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Anthems and patriotic songs<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>DEU</b> 1714-1788<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=10'>Bach, Carl Philipp Emanuel<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Expressive, sensitive, turbulent, rhetoric, polished, dramatic, lucid style, delicate and tender expression, unpredictable. Empfindsamer Stil.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>DEU</b> 1714-1787<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=118'>Gluck, Christoph Willibald von<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Opera revolution by fusing Italian and French traditions in France. Adds drama. Wagner drama precursor.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>AUT</b> 1732-1809<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=138'>Haydn, (Franz) Joseph<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >First Viennese School<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Perky. Can build the whole piece from one melody, likes to reorder themes. Surprising the listener with many unexpected turns and twists. Sudden key changes, unexpected shifts of rhythm or harmony, rests, a phrase that leads into something totally different than what is expected. Idiosyncrasies and eccentric ideas. Closely juxtapose remote keys, suddenly changing from one key to a distant one, with no preparation. Mediocre operas, church and concertos.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ITA</b> 1743-1805<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=32'>Boccherini, Luigi<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Repetitiveness, extended passages with fascinating textures but virtually no melodic line, soft dynamics, introverted and mournful affects. Courtly, galante. Prominent cello. Resembles Haydn.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>DEU</b> 1745-1801<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=259'>Stamitz, Carl<br><td bgcolor=white >Mannheim School<br><td bgcolor=white >Resembles Mozart and Haydn. Appealing melodies, but not excessively virtuosic. Regular periods. Violinist. Prefered minor keys as Richter.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ITA</b> 1750-1825<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=235'>Salieri, Antonio<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Cosmopolitan<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>AUT</b> 1756-1791<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=192'>Mozart, Wolfgang Amadeus<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >First Viennese School<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Happy, flow, melodic, soulful, breath, dramatic, life. Prepare the listener for the intrusion of a remote key by gradually introducing it. Multiple themes, rarely reorders themes. Conservative, regular, well-behaved. Cool operas, church and concertos.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>DEU</b> 1770-1827<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=19'>Beethoven, Ludwig van<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >First Viennese School<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Monumental, sonatas, dramatic, expressive, independent, structural. Far from baroque. Sudden and unexpected pause and the unexpected fermata. False recapitulation. Build movement from one melody. Can be playful and humorous; dramatic and powerful; dreamy and introspective.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>IRL</b> 1782-1837<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=101'>Field, John<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Nocturne inverntor. Chromatically decorated melody over sonorous left hand parts supported by sensitive pedalling.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ITA</b> 1782-1840<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=203'>Paganini, Niccol`o<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Energetic, virtuoso, gypsy. Technically imaginative, imitates instruments and animals. Expanded timbre. Not truly polyphonic. Supportive orchestras.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>DEU</b> 1786-1826<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=291'>Weber, Carl Maria von<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Beautiful woodwind.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>DEU</b> 1791-1864<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=187'>Meyerbeer, Giacomo<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Appealing short-breathed melody, rich harmonic vocabulary, brilliant and novel orchestral effect. Limited thematic development and contrapuntal combination.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>ITA</b> 1792-1868<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=230'>Rossini, Gioacchino Antonio<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Classical, bravura performances, Rossini crescendo. Dense.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>ITA</b> 1797-1848<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=88'>Donizetti, Gaetano<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Catchy tunes, music specific to words, easy come-easy go, coarse, vulgar, cheap, ostentatious, gaudy, tacky. Close to operetta.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>AUT</b> 1797-1828<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=245'>Schubert, Franz Peter<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >First Viennese School<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Lyrical, song. Simple symphonies. Cello.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ITA</b> 1801-1835<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=20'>Bellini, Vincenzo<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Sweet melancholy, long singing lines. Most beautiful.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>FRA</b> 1803-1869<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=23'>Berlioz, Hector<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Pathos, bravura, excess, huge orchestras. Romantic, but very ahead-of-time, eccentric. Did not use chromaticism much (as Wagner, Chopin). Respected Beethoven, Gluck, Mozart, Rossini, Meyerbeer, Verdi. Unique mixture of an innovative modernist and a backward-looking conservative. Despised what he saw as the showy effects of the Italian style and longed to return opera to the dramatic truth of Gluck.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>RUS</b> 1804-1857<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=117'>Glinka, Mikhail Ivanovich<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Simple music with folclore theme<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>DEU</b> 1809-1847<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=183'>Mendelssohn-Bartholdy, Felix<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Insipid, cheerful, anti-radical, conservative, youthful. Pleasant and evocative, without the strong passions, opinions or inner turmoil. Not programmatic.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>POL</b> 1810-1849<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=61'>Chopin, Frederic Francois<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Romantic, poetic, subdued, melancholy, peaceful. Transparence, clarity, ardour. Feminine.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>DEU</b> 1810-1856<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=247'>Schumann, Robert Alexander<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Story, romanticism. Less melody, more symphony. Downcast, grief, boredom. Sand and jewels. Attractive and balanced rather than powerful. Pleasant and evocative, without the strong passions, opinions or inner turmoil.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>HUN</b> 1811-1886<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=168'>Liszt, Franz<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >New German School<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Window-dressing. Piano technique. Variations, dry, masculine. A never ending waterfall of sounds, even in slow variations. "talkative" music. Harmonic adventurousness<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>ITA</b> 1813-1901<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=283'>Verdi, Giuseppe<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Simple, pauses, popular, lyrical, measured.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>DEU</b> 1813-1883<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=288'>Wagner, Richard<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Neoromanticism<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Long pieces, long instrumental parts in operas, heroic, masculine, mighty, tragic. Symphonic music with vocal. Closer to greece tragedy.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>FRA</b> 1818-1893<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=125'>Gounod, Charles<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Romantic, light.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>DEU/FRA</b> 1819-1880<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=199'>Offenbach, Jacques<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Operetta. Influenced J Strauss II and Sullivan.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>BEL/FRA</b> 1822-1890<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=103'>Franck, Cesar<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Contrapuntal, cyclic, frequent graceful modulations. Humility, simplicity, reverence.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>AUT</b> 1824-1896<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=42'>Bruckner, Anton<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Defined contemporary musical radicalism, dissonances, unprepared modulations, roving harmonies. Complex symphonies. Powerful codas, grand finales, frequent use of unison passages and orchestral tutti.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>BOH</b> 1824-1884<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=255'>Smetana, Bedrich<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Czech nationalism, realism and neo-romanticism. Descriptive/programmatic music.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>AUT</b> 1825-1899<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=264'>Strauss II, Johann<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Dancing music<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>RUS</b> 1833-1887<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=34'>Borodin, Alexander<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Five<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Simple, naive, russian, eastern. Absolute music in string quartets, based in thematic structure and instrumental texture on Mendelssohn quartets.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>DEU</b> 1833-1897<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=38'>Brahms, Johannes<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Richness, serious, mellow, emotional, conservative<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>FRA</b> 1835-1921<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=234'>Saint-Saens, Camille<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Works are technically difficult and transparent. Defended Liszt, Wagner, Meyerbeer, Berlioz. Fighted Debussy, Strauss. Later chamber music is more experimental, progressive, abandons lyricism and charm for more profound expression. His piano music is between Liszt and Ravel. Rejected to publish humorous Carnaval of animals until his death. Creativity does not keep pace with his technical skill. His incomparable talent for orchestration enables him to give relief to ideas which would otherwise be crude and mediocre in themselves. His works are on the one hand not frivolous enough to become popular in the widest sense, nor on the other do they take hold of the public by that sincerity and warmth of feeling which is so convincing. Deeply aware of the great masters of the past: Rameau, Bach, Handel, Mozart, Haydn. Makes his effects more by characterful harmony and rhythms than by extravagant scoring. An occasional tendency to neoclassicism, influenced by his study of French baroque music, is in contrast with the colourful orchestral music more widely identified with him. Less attracted than some of his French contemporaries to the continuous stream of music popularised by Wagner, he often favoured self-contained melodies. Though they are frequently supple and pliable, more often than not they are constructed in three- or four-bar sections, and the phrase pattern AABB is characteristic. Rhythmically, he inclined to standard double, triple or compound metres. Master of counterpoint.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>FRA</b> 1836-1891<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=79'>Delibes, Leo<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Influence on Tchaikovsky, Saint-Saëns and Debussy. Charm, wealth of melody. Light, graceful, elegant music, with a tendency toward exoticism - reflects the spirit of the Second Empire in France.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>RUS</b> 1837-1910<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=13'>Balakirev, Mily<br><td bgcolor=white >Five<br><td bgcolor=white >Whole tone scale. Orientalism.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>FRA</b> 1838-1875<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=29'>Bizet, Georges<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Dramatic opera, deep emotions, realistic, melodic, confident. Music that makes no pretensions to depth, but it is delightful in its simplicity, so unaffected and sincere.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>DEU</b> 1838-1920<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=41'>Bruch, Max<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Romantic solo strings.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>RUS</b> 1839-1881<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=193'>Mussorgsky, Modest Petrovich<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Five<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Russian. Pictures. Dances. Romantic but strikingly novel.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>RUS</b> 1840-1893<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=276'>Tchaikovsky, Pyotr Ilich<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Sweet, inexhaustible, supersensuous fund of melody. Themes are "expressively full" and tend to unwind broadly; their clear periodic structure can be disguised by the very expansiveness of the individual phrase and by its sequential extension, which may be prolonged. Foreground projection of a background outline. Typical russian stasis and repetition, self-contained melodies. Melodic sequences. Folclor sources.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>CZE</b> 1841-1904<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=95'>Dvorak, Antonin (Leopold)<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Singing melody. Close to Rachmaninov. Crying through laugh. Pop touching music. Primitive, national.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>FRA</b> 1842-1912<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=182'>Massenet, Jules<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Successfull suave and elegant style. Old-fashioned, unadventurous. Main influences: Gounod and Thomas, with Meyerbeer and Berlioz also important to his style. Some traits from Verdi, Mascagni, Wagner. Unlike some other French composers of the period, Massenet never fell fully under Wagner spell, but he took from the earlier composer a richness of orchestration and a fluency in treatment of musical themes. Much of his music is soft and delicate, although he could write loud, noisy and dissonant scenes. Sensual side is balanced by strong dramatic tension (as in Werther), theatrical action (as in Thérèse), scenic diversion (as in Esclarmonde), or humour (as in Le portrait de Manon).<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ENG</b> 1842-1900<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=267'>Sullivan, Sir Arthur<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Comic, conservative musical style, clarity. Trained in the classical style, and contemporary music did not greatly attract him. Used conventional formulae of Auber, Donizetti, Balfe and Schubert. Later drew on Gounod, Bizet, Mendelssohn, while remaining recognisably himself. In the field of harmony remained an eclectic, had easily recognisable habits but his style never achieved individuality. Preferred major keys. Simultaneous presentation of two or more distinct melodies previously heard independently. Exploiting all registers and colours of clarinet, and particular fond for oboe solos. Tunes, at least in the comic operas, appeal to the professional as much as to the layman: his continental contemporaries such as Debussy, Leoncavallo and Saint-Saens held the Savoy operas in high regard. Although his melodies sprang from rhythm, some of his themes may have been prompted by his chosen instrumentation or his harmonic techniques.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>NOR</b> 1843-1907<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=128'>Grieg, Edvard<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Close to Chopin, Mendelssohn. Chilly, picturesque, traditional, lyrical, programmatic, national. Miniaturist. Attractive and balanced rather than powerful.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>RUS</b> 1844-1908<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=226'>Rimsky-Korsakov, Nikolay<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Five<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Teacher, orchestra. Whole tone scale. Orientalism. Harmonic adventurousness like Liszt. Russian folklore.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>FRA</b> 1845-1924<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=99'>Faure, Gabriel<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Roundish, harmonic, naive. Linking end of Romanticism with modernism. Advanced, harmonic and melodic innovations. No radical difference between first and last compositions. Developed compositional techniques that foreshadowed atonal music of Schoenberg, and drew discreetly on the techniques of jazz. Early influences by Chopin, Mozart, Schumann. Restraint and beauty of surface from Mozart, tonal freedom and long melodic lines from Chopin. From Schumann - sudden felicities in which his development sections abound, and those codas in which whole movements are briefly but magically illuminated. By using unresolved mild discords and colouristic effects, Faure anticipated techniques of Impressionist composers. In contrast with his harmonic and melodic style, which pushed the bounds for his time, Faure rhythmic motives tended to be subtle and repetitive, with little to break the flow of the line, although he used discreet syncopations, similar to those found in Brahms works. Piano works often use arpeggiated figures, with the melody interspersed between the two hands. Student of Saint-Saens.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>CZE</b> 1854-1928<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=150'>Janacek, Leos<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Folklorist<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Folclore, minimalism<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1854-1932<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=257'>Sousa, John Philip<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >American military and patriotic marches. Simple, sometimes jazzy.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ENG</b> 1857-1934<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=96'>Elgar, Sir Edward<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Contemptuous of folk music. Influenced by Handel, Dvorak, Brahms, Purcell. Chromaticism after Wagner. Orchestration after Berlioz, Massenet, Saint-Saens, Delibes. Assembling compositions from scraps of themes jotted down randomly. Orchestral genius, modern.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ITA</b> 1857-1919<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=165'>Leoncavallo, Ruggero<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Verismo.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>ITA</b> 1858-1924<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=216'>Puccini, Giacomo<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Verismo. Shows inner dialogue, sensitive and emotional heroes<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>AUT</b> 1860-1911<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=174'>Mahler, Gustav<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Yearning, symphonic song, contrasting moods, progressive tonality, extremes of volume, off-stage ensembles, unconventional arrangement of orchestral forces, frequent recourse to popular music and dance forms <br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>FRA</b> 1862-1918<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=78'>Debussy, Achille-Claude<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Symbolism. Hazy, sound, wishy-washy, mistical, semi-tones, half-tint, lure. Sound of water: flowing, waves, ocean, rain, lake, river, drops. Sensory component and frequent eschewing of tonality. Non-traditional scales and chromaticism. Glittering passages and webs of figurations which distract from occasional absence of tonality. Parallel chords, bitonality, whole-tone and pentatonic scales. Unprepared modulations, without any harmonic bridge.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ITA</b> 1863-1945<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=181'>Mascagni, Pietro<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Verismo, dramatic, theatral.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>DEU/AUT</b> 1864-1949<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=263'>Strauss, Richard<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Last of the great Romantics. Like his contemporary Gustav Mahler he both followed and greatly extended the type of musical expression founded by composers such as Richard Wagner where highly charged music was performed by enormous orchestras. Programmatic music.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>FRA</b> 1865-1935<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=91'>Dukas, Paul<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >At a time when French musicians were divided into conservative and progressive factions, Dukas adhered to neither but retained the admiration of both. His compositions were influenced by composers including Beethoven, Berlioz, Franck, Debussy. Self-critical, destroyed many compositions.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>RUS</b> 1865-1936<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=115'>Glazunov, Alexander Konstantinovich<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Successfully reconciled nationalism and cosmopolitanism in Russian music. While he was the direct successor to Balakirev nationalism, he tended more towards Borodin epic grandeur while absorbing influences of Rimsky-Korsakov orchestral virtuosity, Tchaikovsky lyricism, Taneyev contrapuntal skill. His weaknesses were a streak of academicism which sometimes overpowered his inspiration and an eclecticism which could sap the ultimate stamp of originality from his music. Younger composers such as Prokofiev and Shostakovich eventually considered his music old-fashioned while also admitting he remained a composer with an imposing reputation and a stabilizing influence in a time of transition and turmoil. Students: Shostakovich.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>DNK</b> 1865-1931<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=195'>Nielsen, Carl<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >National.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>FIN</b> 1865-1957<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=254'>Sibelius, Jean<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Anti-modernism<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Natural, forest, national. Calls Wagner pompous and vulgar. Sibelius progressively stripped away formal markers of sonata form in his work and, instead of contrasting multiple themes, he focused on the idea of continuously evolving cells and fragments culminating in a grand statement. His later works are remarkable for their sense of unbroken development, progressing by means of thematic permutations and derivations. Self-contained structure is in stark contrast to the symphonic style of Gustav Mahler. While thematic variation played a major role in the works of both composers, Mahler style made use of disjunct, abruptly changing and contrasting themes, while Sibelius sought to slowly transform thematic elements. Severity of symphonic style and the profound logic that created an inner connection between all the motifs. Similarities to Bruckner: unmixed timbral palette and sombre brass chorales of Sibelius orchestration, a fondness for pedal points, and in the underlying slow pace of the music. New chord patterns, including naked tritones, bare melodic structures to build long movements of music, in a manner similar to Joseph Haydn use of built-in dissonances. Often alternate melodic sections with noble brass chords that would swell and fade away, or he would underpin his music with repeating figures which push against the melody and counter-melody. Melodies often feature powerful modal implications (Dorian mode in Symphony 6). Influence of Renaissance polyphony. Often varied his movements in a piece by changing the note values of melodies, rather than the conventional change of tempi. Often draw out one melody over a number of notes, while playing a different melody in shorter rhythm. For example, his Seventh Symphony comprises four originally sketched movements fused into telescopical and partly parallel functions without pause, where every important theme is in C major or C minor; the variation comes from the time and rhythm. His harmonic language was often restrained, even iconoclastic, compared to many of his contemporaries who were already experimenting with musical Modernism. Celestial timbres.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ITA</b> 1866-1924<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=46'>Busoni, Ferruccio<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Contrapuntally complex, with several melodic lines unwinding at once. Never entirely atonal, but often indeterminate key. Many of Busonis works are based on music of the past (Bach). Most works are transcriptions of Bach and other composers.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>FRA</b> 1866-1925<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=238'>Satie, Erik<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Avant-garde<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Structure, glass, fragile. Precursor to minimalism. Eccentric composer of weird little ditties. Miniatures for the piano which seemed very much to defy any of the expected conventions of music. Outwardly simple, straightforward in terms of harmony, using short melodies with little development, even repetitive at times. Used unusual scales such as the old form of modes, and others of uncertain origin suggesting folk tunes from different parts of the world. Non-conformist, avand-garde father. First to use jazz and ragtime.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1868-1917<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=152'>Joplin, Scott<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Merges belcanto with ragtime.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>DEU</b> 1869-1949<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=326'>Pfitzner, Hans<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Regressive modernist. Too progressive and too conservative (in terms of Schoenberg). Combines Romantic and Late Romantic elements with extended thematic development, atmospheric music drama, and the intimacy of chamber music. Known for Palestrina.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>AUT</b> 1870-1948<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=164'>Lehar, Franz<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Operetta.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>RUS</b> 1872-1915<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=249'>Scriabin, Alexander<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Phylosophycal, cosmic, abstract. First period resembles Chopin. Later tonality has been attenuated to the point of virtual extinction, although dominant sevenths, which are among the strongest indicators of tonallty, preponderate. The progression of their roots in minor thirds or diminished fifths dissipate the suggested tonality. Acoustic, octatonic, nine-note scales.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>ENG</b> 1872-1958<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=282'>Vaughan Williams, Ralph<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Emotional, english folklore tunes, oriental, atmospheric. Earlier works influenced by Ravel. Wasps start sounds like real wasps flying.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>RUS/USA</b> 1873-1943<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=219'>Rachmaninov, Sergey Vasilyevich<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Nostalgia, simple, smile, light, near-impressionist, clear textures, bell chords (widely spaced). Pianist. Brutal gestures and uncompromising power of expression, unprecedented in Russian music at the time. Flexible rhythms, sweeping lyricism and stringent economy of thematic material. Sumptuous harmonies and broadly lyrical, often passionate melodies. Orthodox chants. Song-like melodicism, expressiveness and his use of rich orchestral colors.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>AUT/USA</b> 1874-1951<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=244'>Schoenberg, Arnold<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Second Viennese School, Neoclassicism<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Rigorous, 12-tone<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>USA</b> 1874-1954<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=149'>Ives, Charles Edward<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >American Five, Microtonal<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Noble. Aleatoric music. Microtonal. Polytonality, polyrhythm, tone clusters. Quotations. Combined the American popular and church-music traditions of his youth with European art music. Sources of Ives tonal imagery are hymn tunes and traditional songs, the town band at holiday parade, the fiddlers at Saturday night dances, patriotic songs, sentimental parlor ballads, and the melodies of Stephen Foster.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ENG</b> 1874-1934<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=143'>Holst, Gustav<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Direct, concise, obvious, simplicity, economy of expression. Known for The Planets. Unconventional time signatures, rising and falling scales, ostinato, bitonality and occasional polytonality - set him apart from other English composers.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>FRA</b> 1875-1937<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=221'>Ravel, Maurice<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Folklorist, Neoclassicism<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Impressionism, modernism, spanish folklore, exoticism, archaism. Clockwork, industrial area, perfectionist. Known especially for his melodies, orchestral and instrumental textures and effects. Synthesist of disparate styles. Applied the aesthetics of the new French school of Chabrier, Satie, and particularly Debussy, rather than atonal Schoenberg. Compositions rely upon modal melodies (dorian, phrygian). Extended harmonies and intricate modulations. Writes in the style of other composers (Gounod, Chabrier, Haydn, Faure). Often masked the sections of his structure with transitions that disguised the beginnings of the motif. Student of Faure.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>RUS</b> 1875-1956<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=116'>Gli`ere, Reinhold<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Incorporating elements of the folk music of Russia, Ukraine, and surrounding republics.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ESP</b> 1876-1946<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=98'>Falla, Manuel de<br><td bgcolor=white >Folklorist, Neoclassicism<br><td bgcolor=white >Folklorist, impressionist, neo-classicist.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1876-1971<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=233'>Ruggles, Carl<br><td bgcolor=white >Ultramodern, American Five<br><td bgcolor=white >Atonal, firm, coarse, fundamental, principled. Finely crafted pieces using "dissonant counterpoint" (avoiding repeating a pitch class until a generally fixed number such as eight pitch classes intervened). Wrote slowly. Trial and error (improvised and listened). "Ives without melodies". Dynamic and pitch waves.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>AUT</b> 1878-1934<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=337'>Schreker, Franz<br><td bgcolor=white >Expressionist<br><td bgcolor=white >Opera.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>HUN</b> 1881-1945<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=16'>Bartok, Bela<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Folklorist<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Most climactic and barbaric. Folclore+dissonances. Collection and analytical study of folk music.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>RUS/FRA/USA</b> 1882-1971<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=265'>Stravinsky, Igor<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Folklorist<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Cosmopolitan. Rimsky-korsakov/Tchaikovsky/Wagner/Dvorak/Debussy influence. Russian folk tunes. Rhythmically off-balance by frequent meter changes and unpredictable accents. Russian/Neoclassical/Serial periods. Additive motivic development. Clashing ostinati.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>POL</b> 1882-1937<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=271'>Szymanowski, Karol<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Used quartertones on the violin in Myths Op. 30<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>AUT</b> 1883-1945<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=292'>Webern, Anton<br><td bgcolor=white >Second Viennese School, Neoclassicism<br><td bgcolor=white >Jewel, short, transparent, concise, distilled, select. Very loud and very quiet parts. Made atonal language more popular by organizing it into clear linear forms and not piling up. Insisted on lyricism, nuance, rubato, sensitivity, and both emotional and intellectual understanding in performance of music. Spartan textures, in which every note can be clearly heard; carefully chosen timbres, often resulting in very detailed instructions to the performers and use of extended instrumental techniques (flutter tonguing, col legno...); wide-ranging melodic lines, often with leaps greater than an octave<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>FRA</b> 1883-1965<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=281'>Var`ese, Edgard<br><td bgcolor=white >Ultramodern, Microtonal, sonorism<br><td bgcolor=white >Emphasizes timbre and rhythm. Inventor of "organized sound" (timbres and rhythms grouped together). Challenged traditional conceptions of noise and found ways to transform noise into music. "Early Stravinsky without folk melodies".<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>AUT</b> 1885-1935<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=21'>Berg, Alban<br><td bgcolor=white >Second Viennese School, Neoclassicism<br><td bgcolor=white >Liked Mahler, Strauss. Popular romantic of Schoenberg school. Two sides: lush and branching Mahler-like melodies, nostalgy for sweet sounds and mathematical complexity for complexity.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1885-1945<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=308'>Kern, Jerome<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >American composer of musical theatre and popular music<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>ESP</b> 1935-<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=313'>Young, La Monte<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Drone minimalism<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >First minimalist. Drone. Microtonal.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>BRA</b> 1887-1959<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=285'>Villa-Lobos, Heitor<br><td bgcolor=white >Neoclassicism<br><td bgcolor=white >Merges Stravinsky rhythms with afrobrazilian form.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>RUS</b> 1891-1953<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=215'>Prokofiev, Sergey<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Sardonic, quirky. Resembles Stravinsky. Uses satire in his music, although not as bitterly sarcastic as Shostakovich. Master of the orchestra, drama and dance. Entirely logical but not very predictable. Obeyed normal musical conventions, while allowing itself to jump off at tangents from time to time.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>FRA</b> 1892-1974<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=188'>Milhaud, Darius<br><td bgcolor=white >Les Six, Neoclassicism<br><td bgcolor=white >Polytonality. Influenced by jazz, brazilian popular music.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>DEU/USA</b> 1895-1963<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=142'>Hindemith, Paul<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Neoclassicism<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Early works are in a late romantic idiom, and he later produced expressionist works, rather in the style of early Arnold Schoenberg, before developing a leaner, contrapuntally complex style. Very different neoclassicism from the works by Stravinsky labeled with that term, owing more to contrapuntal language of Bach and Reger than the Classical clarity of Mozart. Unusual small instrumental ensembles. One traditional aspect of classical music that Hindemith retains is the idea of dissonance resolving to consonance. Much of his music begins in consonant territory, progresses rather smoothly into dissonance, and resolves at the end in full, consonant chords. Tonal but non-diatonic. Like most tonal music, it is centered on a tonic and modulates from one tonal center to another, but it uses all 12 notes freely rather than relying on a scale picked as a subset of these notes. <br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1895-1978<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=328'>Still, William Grant<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >First afro-american conductor and composer.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1896-1989<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=309'>Thomson, Virgil<br><td bgcolor=white >Neoclassicism, Neoromanticism, Copland group<br><td bgcolor=white >Critic. Olympian blend of humanity and detachment.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1897-1965<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=72'>Cowell, Henry<br><td bgcolor=white >Ultramodern, American Five<br><td bgcolor=white >Aleatoric music.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>USA</b> 1898-1937<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=109'>Gershwin, George<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Jazz composer who wrote the first serious and highly regarded classical music in that idiom.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1898-1979<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=334'>Harris, Roy<br><td bgcolor=white >Neoclassicism, Copland group<br><td bgcolor=white >Music on American subjects. Research into and use of folk music (and to a lesser extent of jazz rhythms). Obsessed with the great European pre-classical forms, especially the fugue and passacaglia. Long singing lines and resonant modal harmonies, is ultimately based on his admiration for and development of Renaissance polyphony. Antiphonal effects. Like many American composers of his time, he was deeply impressed by the symphonic achievement of Sibelius. Music grows organically from the opening bars, as if a tiny seed gives birth to an entire tree.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>FRA</b> 1899-1963<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=213'>Poulenc, Francis<br><td bgcolor=white >Les Six<br><td bgcolor=white >Diatonic, melodic. Early works: high spirits, irreverence, humorous, lightweight, simple melodies, pleasing, easily remembered, often emotionally expressive. Later: much more serious side, particularly in the religious music.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>DEU/USA</b> 1900-1950<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=294'>Weill, Kurt<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Music that served a socially useful purpose. Threepenny Opera, including Mack the knife (later became jazz standard).<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>USA</b> 1900-1990<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=66'>Copland, Aaron<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Neoclassicism<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Expansive melodic sweep and novel rhythmic drive. Experimentalist, incorporates Jazz and Mexican dance rhythms in his music. The spirit of America. Deceptively simple from a casual acquaintance yet with a hidden richness and depth. Break away from the European-centric world of previous classical music.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1900-1991<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=306'>Krenek, Ernst<br><td bgcolor=white >Neoclassicism, Zeitoper<br><td bgcolor=white >Centrist composer (mixes tonality and dissonance). Early work in late-Romantic idiom, (influence of teacher Franz Schreker). Later turned to atonality, neo-classical, jazz opera, 12-tone, total serialism, aleatoric. Later relaxed.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1901-1974<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=325'>Partch, Harry<br><td bgcolor=white >Microtonal<br><td bgcolor=white >First to work systematically with microtonal scales. His earliest compositions were small-scale pieces to be intoned to instrumental backing; his later works were large-scale, integrated theater productions in which he expected each of the performers to sing, dance, speak, and play instruments. Ancient Greek theatre and Japanese Noh and kabuki heavily influenced his music theatre. Built a large number of unique instruments to play his just scales.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1901-1953<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=327'>Seeger, Ruth Crawford<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Modernist woman composer.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ENG</b> 1902-1983<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=289'>Walton, William<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Old-fashioned, bittersweet, nostalgic. Rhythmic vitality, sensuous melancholy, sly charm and orchestral flair. Facade - first and only modernist work. Assimilated anglican anthems, jazz, and the music of Stravinsky, Sibelius, Ravel and Elgar. Fast moving score full of syncopation and cross-rhythm. Symphony 1 is reminiscent of Sibelius. Viola concerto: despite the common influence of jazz and of the music of Hindemith and Ravel, in its structure and romantic longing it owes much to the Elgar Cello Concerto. Slow worker, painstakingly perfectionist. <br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>DEU/USA</b> 1902-1972<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=314'>Wolpe, Stefan<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Fresh perspective on atonality. Despite excursions into popular, folk and jazz idioms, Wolpe continued to compose in atonal styles throughout his career. Cross-cutting and discontinuity between different musical gestures and textures (Dadaism). Early compositions use the 12-tone techniques of Schoenberg and the Second Viennese School. Irregular rhythms and contrapuntal textures. Avoids isolated points of sound (pointillism) which was common to Schoenberg and his followers. Influenced by jazz and popular dance music. Workers songs and pieces that satirized society. Simplified his dense, atonal writing, making it more accessible to people without musical training. He does everything wrong and it comes out right. <br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ITA</b> 1905-1988<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=336'>Scelsi, Giacinto<br><td bgcolor=white >Microtonal, sonorism<br><td bgcolor=white >Best known for writing music based around only one pitch, altered in all manners through microtonal oscillations, harmonic allusions, and changes in timbre and dynamics. Close to ritual chanting of Tibetan monks.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>RUS</b> 1906-1975<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=253'>Shostakovich, Dmitri<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Tragic and tormented, bitterness, cold, most reserved, emo.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>FRA</b> 1908-1992<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=186'>Messiaen, Olivier<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Darmstadt School<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Ecstasy, total serialism. Used birdsongs and exotic music: Indonesian gamelan, Japanese, Greek, Hindu rhythms. Tuned percussion. Modes of limited transposition. Outside western musical tradition, although growing out of that tradition and being influenced by it. Denies the western conventions of forward motion, development and diatonic harmonic resolution. Piano often sounds like bells.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ITA</b> 1925-2003<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=22'>Berio, Luciano<br><td bgcolor=white >Darmstadt School<br><td bgcolor=white >Collage. Experimental, virtuosic solo, electronic music pioneer. Whisper, shout, sing.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1910-1981<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=15'>Barber, Samuel<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Musical logic, sense of architectural design, effortless melodic gift, and direct emotional appeal. Long melodic phrases and lush orchestration. Studied Bach, Brahms. Built on romantic structures and sensibilities, is at once lyrical, rhythmically complex, and harmonically rich.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>FRA</b> 1910-1995<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=317'>Schaeffer, Pierre<br><td bgcolor=white >Musique concrete, sonorism<br><td bgcolor=white >Noise music. Tape looping. Sound collage. Electroacoustic improvisation.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>USA</b> 1912-1992<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=50'>Cage, John<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Darmstadt School, New York School<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Aleatoric music.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>USA</b> 1932-<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=296'>Williams, John<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Film<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Firmly from the classical tradition, based heavily on the style of the late-romantics such as Gustav Mahler and Richard Strauss. It has at times some modernistic overtones (such as with Close Encounters of the third kind), yet primarily it is just wholesome music full of good memorable tunes with fanfares and fun marches particularly prominent. Williams is rightly well-regarded for his ability to construct a tune and sound which perfectly complements the mood of a film.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>MEX</b> 1912-1997<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=323'>Nancarrow, Conlon<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Punching machine (piano). Blues.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>ENG</b> 1913-1976<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=40'>Britten, Benjamin<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc > <br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Studied with Frank Bridge. Uses popular tunes. Tonal music. Introduced atonalism in Death in Venice. Progressive conservatism. Avoided avantgarde.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>POL</b> 1913-1994<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=171'>Lutoslawski, Witold<br><td bgcolor=white >Avant-garde, sonorism<br><td bgcolor=white >Aleatoric music. Influence of Polish folk music, both harmonically and melodically. 12 tone. Unsynchronized parts of ensemble.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1916-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=9'>Babbitt, Milton<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Jerky. 12-tone<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1918-1990<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=24'>Bernstein, Leonard<br><td bgcolor=white >Boston School<br><td bgcolor=white >Mainly tonal. Eclectic: jazz, theatre, jewish, Copland, Stravinsky, Milhaud, Gershwin. Bridge the gap between classical and popular music.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>DEU</b> 1918-1970<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=335'>Zimmermann, Bernd Alois<br><td bgcolor=white >Klangkomposition<br><td bgcolor=white >Neoclassical. Dark, depressive, tragic, painful, desperate, 12-tone. Collage, music quotation. In contrast to Darmstadt school, he did not make a radical break with tradition. Combination and overlapping of layers of musical material from various time periods (from Medieval to Baroque and Classical to Jazz and Pop music) using advanced musical techniques<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ARG</b> 1921-1992<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=301'>Piazzolla, Astor<br><td bgcolor=white >Nuevo Tango<br><td bgcolor=white >Revolutionized the traditional tango into a new style termed nuevo tango, incorporating elements from jazz, counterpoint and classical music, extended compositional forms.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>GRC/FRA</b> 1922-2001<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=298'>Xenakis, Iannis<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Darmstadt School, sonirism<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Mathematical models in music. Shock. Extremeties. Microtonal.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1962-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=141'>Higdon, Jennifer<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >tonal, octatonal, a little atonal<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>HUN</b> 1923-2006<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=167'>Ligeti, Gyorgy<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Avant-garde, sonorism<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Organ. Symphonic Poem for 100 Metronomes. Orchestral microphlyphony. Microtonal.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ITA</b> 1924-1990<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=196'>Nono, Luigi<br><td bgcolor=white >Darmstadt School<br><td bgcolor=white >Microtonal.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>FRA</b> 1925-<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=36'>Boulez, Pierre<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Darmstadt School<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Furious, most relaxed in a spazz sort of way, total serialism. Aleatoric music. Example of serial music with quartertones in his pieces Visage Nuptial and Polyphonie X.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1926-1987<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=100'>Feldman, Morton<br><td bgcolor=white >New York School<br><td bgcolor=white >Pioneer of indeterminate music. Notational innovations that he developed to create his characteristic sound: rhythms that seem to be free and floating; pitch shadings that seem softly unfocused; a generally quiet and slowly evolving music; recurring asymmetric patterns. His later works, after 1977, also begin to explore extremes of duration. Distributed limited number of sounds in long time intervals. Teachers: Wolpe, Varese. Music flows above non-regular rhythms. Repetitive and even minimalism sometimes.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>DEU</b> 1928-2007<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=260'>Stockhausen, Karlheinz<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Darmstadt School<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Long. Weird. Another planet. Aleatoric music. Microtonal.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>RUS</b> 1931-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=130'>Gubaidulina, Sofia<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Unusual instrumental combinations. Intense chromatic motives rather than long melodic phrases. Micro-chromaticism, glissando. Chromatic as darkness and diatonic as light. Open-ended and disjunct. Resists traditional tonal centers and triadic structures in favor of pitch clusters and intervallic design arising from the contrapuntal interaction between melodic voices. Temporal ratios should not be limited to local figuration; rather, the temporality of the musical form should be the defining feature of rhythmic character. Uses durational ratios in order to create the temporal forms for her compositions (Fibonacci sequence, Golden ratio). Compositions for bayan sound like synthesizers.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1931-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=321'>Lucier, Alvin<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Experimental music and sound installations that explore acoustic phenomena and auditory perception. Much of his work is influenced by science and explores the physical properties of sound itself: resonance of spaces, phase interference between closely tuned pitches, and the transmission of sound through physical media. Encephalogram, reverberation, triangle, teapot.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ARG</b> 1931-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=319'>Kagel, Mauricio<br><td bgcolor=white >Darmstadt School<br><td bgcolor=white >Absurdist. Collage with distortion. Theatrical instructions to performers. Close to Cage. Organ. Anti-theoretical.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>POL</b> 1933-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=206'>Penderecki, Krzysztof<br><td bgcolor=white >Sonorism<br><td bgcolor=white >Gangsta. Microtonal. Tone clusters. Experimental textures, baroque form, occasional traditional harmonic and melodic writing, serialism in St. Luke Passion. Later focused on semitones and tritones, Bruckner. Extended instrumental techniques in Threnody.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1933-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=329'>Subotnick, Morton<br><td bgcolor=white >Electronic music<br><td bgcolor=white >One of the pioneers in the development of electronic music and multi-media performance and an innovator in works involving instruments and other media, including interactive computer music systems. Most of his music calls for a computer part, or live electronic processing; his oeuvre utilizes many of the important technological breakthroughs in the history of the genre.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ENG</b> 1934-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=28'>Birtwistle, Sir Harrison<br><td bgcolor=white >New Music Manchester<br><td bgcolor=white >Comic quoting. Complex, written in a modernistic manner with a clear, distinctive voice. Early work sometimes evocative of Stravinsky and Messiaen, ostinati, ritualistic. Technique of juxtaposing blocks of sound is compared to Edgar Varese.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>RUS</b> 1934-1998<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=243'>Schnittke, Alfred<br><td bgcolor=white >New Simplicity<br><td bgcolor=white >Polistylism, combines various styles: past and present, serious and light. Later withdrawn, bleak style.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ENG/SCO</b> 1934-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=318'>Davies, Peter Maxwell<br><td bgcolor=white >New Music Manchester<br><td bgcolor=white >Comic quoting. Early works often use serial techniques, sometimes combined with Mediaeval and Renaissance compositional methods. Fragments of plainsong are often used as basic source material to be adapted and developed in various ways. Later experimantal and violent. Polystylism. Uses magic squares. Later style compares to Sibelius. Later works much more accessible (no longer a modernist).<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>DEU</b> 1935-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=320'>Lachenmann, Helmut<br><td bgcolor=white >Musique concrete instrumentale<br><td bgcolor=white >Invented new techniques for wind, brass and string instruments. Uses whisper. Distorted fragments of other styles. Thorough works. Strained attention.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>EST</b> 1935-<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=205'>Part, Arvo<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Holy minimalism<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Holy minimalism. Tintinnabuli. Beautiful.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1935-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=332'>Riley, Terry<br><td bgcolor=white >Minimalism<br><td bgcolor=white >Minimalism pioneer. Jazz, indian music. Microtonal.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>USA</b> 1936-<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=223'>Reich, Steve<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Minimalism<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Minimalism pioneer. Hypnotic, concentrated<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>USA</b> 1937-<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=114'>Glass, Philip<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Minimalism<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Minimalism pioneer. Concentrated, simple, repetitive, gradual change<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1938-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=33'>Bolcom, William<br><td bgcolor=white >Neoromanticism, Eclectism<br><td bgcolor=white >Serialism, eclectic use of wide variety of musical styles. Wants to erase boundaries between popular and art music. Showtunes, parlour, and popular songs from the late 19th and early 20th century, by Henry Russell, Henry Clay Work, and others, and cabaret songs (often from failed musicals).<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ENG</b> 1943-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=330'>Ferneyhough, Brian<br><td bgcolor=white >New complexity<br><td bgcolor=white >Highly complex notation and the extensive use of irregular nested rhythmic tuplets. Central figure of the New Complexity movement in music. Microtonal. Rejects serialism and other "generative" methods of composing.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>BRI</b> 1944-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=304'>Nyman, Michael Laurence<br><td bgcolor=white >Minimalism<br><td bgcolor=white >Minimalism and film music, piano.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>SWE</b> 1928-2000<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=331'>Hambraeus, Bengt<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Most known for organ compositions.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>FRA</b> 1946-1998<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=315'>Grisey, Gerard<br><td bgcolor=white >Spectral, sonorism<br><td bgcolor=white >Spectral music. Microtonal.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ENG</b> 1939-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=333'>Harvey, Jonathan<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Merges choral with spectral music<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>USA</b> 1947-<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=1'>Adams, John<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Post-minimalism<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Mixes minimalism with romanticism. Steady pulse (minimalism).<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>FRA</b> 1947-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=316'>Murail, Tristan<br><td bgcolor=white >Spectral, sonorism<br><td bgcolor=white >Spectral music. Microtonal.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ARG</b> 1960-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=310'>Golijov, Osvaldo<br><td bgcolor=white >Folklorist<br><td bgcolor=white >Rich musical language: jewish music, argentine tango, other.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ENG</b> 1971-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=322'>Ades, Thomas<br><td bgcolor=white > <br><td bgcolor=white >Uses other styles in his work<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>FRA</b> 1970-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=305'>Tiersen, Yann<br><td bgcolor=white >Pop<br><td bgcolor=white >Best known for Amelie and other film music. Not from classical world. Plays guitar.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>DEU</b> 1957-<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=338'>Zimmer, Hans<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Film electronic<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Integrating electronic music sounds with traditional orchestral arrangements.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1953-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=341'>Elfman, Danny<br><td bgcolor=white >Film<br><td bgcolor=white >Early inspired by Rota Circus and Herrmann style. Tim Burton. Dark and weird but with a wicked humour. In Pee-Wee, Elfman uses good-humoured yet whacky tunes bobbing on top of simple accompaniments which suddenly change direction as though distracted. In Beetlejuice, the bold, dark and bouncy theme which accompanies the opening sequence immediately sets the scene for a romping tour de force, where you just know that something strange will hit you around every corner. In Batman the powerful Gothic theme seems to reverberate from some dark cathedral, with some colourful characterisation for the deranged Joker, and in Edward Scissorhands we have a gentle fairy tale with wonderful imagery (and equally descriptive music) which seems to have escaped from a fairy story rather than a horror movie. Elfman soundscape for Edward Scissorhands has been much copied particularly on television commercials, and the music has now been adapted into a ballet by British composer Terry Davis. Combine and switch influences from classical, early film music, blues, jazz, pop and various ethnic styles. Percussion is core to his music.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1911-1975<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=342'>Herrmann, Bernard<br><td bgcolor=white >Film<br><td bgcolor=white >Hitchcock trillers. Bird sounds edited together as the soundtrack to The Birds. Bold percussion music. Bold and direct, yet certainly not typical of the day. Rather than full-blown themes, his knack was to select and develop simple mottos such as those high-pitched screaming Psycho violins or in Vertigo those dizzying augmented chord arpeggios that seemed to encapsulate the whole concept of the movie (moving in different directions at the same time). Orchestration also tended to be unusual but again tailored perfectly to the particular need. Psycho used strings only, which seemed to match the black and white photography. Follows Rozsa being bold and dark and an integral part of the film experience. Taxi driver (central theme on saxophone oozing a sleazy Jazz mood for the city night life, and some sweeping dramatic surges to show the Robert de Niro character state of mind). Orchestration also tended to be unusual but again tailored perfectly to the particular need. Psycho used strings only, which seemed to match the black and white photography. In Jason and the Argonauts, he makes use of woodwinds in lower registers and primordial brass fanfares to evoke Hellenic antiquity.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>GRC</b> 1943-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=344'>Vangelis<br><td bgcolor=white >Film electronic<br><td bgcolor=white >Started as rock band. Electronic pioneer. Brooding atmosphere. Instinctive, improvising. Mood music, in part because of the leisurely pace in the classical tradition of Schubert or Bruckner. He is able to create a distinctive sound with simple, repetitive yet memorable tunes against evocative rhythms and chord progressions.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=#ccffcc align=center><b>ITA</b> 1928-<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=345'>Morricone, Ennio<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Film<br><td bgcolor=#ccffcc >Early western movies. Juxtapose different styles. Unusual instrumentation, such as panpipes and banjo. Mix unusual sound combinations and trashy pop elements with an atmosphere of legendary or religious reverence. Mixes hymn-like chorales with poignant solos, wordless ethnic chanting, drums and panpipes to bring out the South American jungle setting. The exhuberant chanting uses short detached notes, an usual effect which Morricone also employed on his well-known piece called Chi Mai.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1967-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=349'>Giacchino, Michael<br><td bgcolor=white >Film<br><td bgcolor=white >Referenced previous work both in style and naming. Violins positioned at the base of the “pyramid”, instead of traditionally having the melody at the top of the “pyramid”. Flutes or piccolos at the top, having the melody in many of his songs. Favor flutes just a little bit more than the trumpets, clarinets, and saxophones. At times wrote parts for saxophones that were playing majority of the length of songs in a score, especially in “The Incredibles” (jazzy), but when the flutes come into the song, despite the saxophones, they contribute more to the song. By the parts they were given by Giacchino, they seemed to be featured in a more important way than the saxophones. Muted trumpets that either share or have the melody of the tune (old-fashioned WW2).<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>CAN</b> 1946-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=350'>Shore, Howard<br><td bgcolor=white >Film<br><td bgcolor=white >Initially horror (Cronenberg), experimental, instinctive. Within traditional orchestral scores he mixed period styles and world music, electronic instruments and sampled sounds.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>DEU</b> 1888-1971<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=351'>Steiner, Max<br><td bgcolor=white >Film father<br><td bgcolor=white >Father of film music. Every character should have a theme. Direct. Doesnt mess about with subtle nuances but gets straight to the point, whatever emotion is required for the movie. Borrowing the occasional tune or idea, at times his music can seem a little cliched to modern ears. Occasionally "Mickey Mousing" the film, i.e. following the action too closely as in a cartoon. Fanfare.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA/HUN</b> 1907-1995<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=353'>Rozsa, Miklos<br><td bgcolor=white >Film<br><td bgcolor=white >Historical Epics and Thillers, Film Noir or Psychological Dramas. Big and direct, though he is also capable of underscoring more delicate scenes. Some music has religious feel. Theremin (mysterious).<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1901-1970<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=354'>Newman, Alfred<br><td bgcolor=white >Film father<br><td bgcolor=white >Musicals, nocturnes, ballet, conductor. Grand lush orchestral music. Jazz.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1955-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=355'>Newman, Thomas<br><td bgcolor=white >Film<br><td bgcolor=white >Likes to vary on the instrumentations for his scores, ranging from full orchestras to percussion-only music. He is also fond of incorporating unusual instruments such as the zither, hurdy-gurdy, psaltery and hammered dulcimer, or unexpected sounds, like Aboriginal chants and the chirping of cicadas. The composer declared that he has "an interest in mundane experimentation."<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>RUS/USA</b> 1894-1979<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=358'>Tiomkin, Dimitri<br><td bgcolor=white >Film father<br><td bgcolor=white >Western scores. American spirit (although trained in Russia). Coming up with themes and finding vivid ways of creating sonic color appropriate to the story and visual image, not in his ability to combine the themes into a complex symphonic structure that could stand on its own.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>FRA</b> 1961-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=361'>Desplat, Alexandre<br><td bgcolor=white >Film<br><td bgcolor=white >Classical+jazz/world. Bass sound, solo timpani. Switch genres effortlessly.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>ITA</b> 1911-1979<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=363'>Rota, Nino<br><td bgcolor=white >Film<br><td bgcolor=white >Federico Fellini, Francis Coppola films. Operas, ballets, orchestral, choral, chamber works.  Good-humoured energy verging on satire. Blend between the theatrical irony of Prokofiev and the impish wit of Francis Poulenc. Sometimes used light jazz idiom, and could be compared with Mancini in some ways. Didnt completely ignore the emotional side of the films, but avoided overly sentimental by seemingly coming at the subject obliquely with a slight sense of the absurd. This slightly detatched feel is a characteristic most closely associated with European cinema, especially Italian and French films. While on the surface this description might sound like a lack of caring, it has often resulted in artisically pleasing and often very poignant, true-to-life stories when compared to the inevitable over-simplified Hollywood remakes. (It can help to think of this as using the whole colour spectrum rather than a patronising black and white). Circus.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>USA</b> 1937-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=364'>Badalamenti, Angelo<br><td bgcolor=white >Film<br><td bgcolor=white >Psychological thrillers, historical dramas. Pop (with strong hints of jazz and a certain weird country feel). Walking chromatic bass and drum kit stroked gently by brushes. Wild songs. Uses R. Strauss Im Abendrot. Repetitive pop-driven cues for tension building and action sequences.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>SRB</b> 1950-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=368'>Bregovic, Goran<br><td bgcolor=white >Film<br><td bgcolor=white >Extending Balkan musical inspirations to innovative extremes, draw upon European classicism and Balkan rhythms. Carries Bosnian, Serbian, Bulgarian, Greek and Romani themes and is a fusion of popular music with traditional polyphonic music from the Balkans, tango and brass bands. Emir Kusturica films.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>RUS</b> 1935-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=369'>Kancheli, Giya<br><td bgcolor=white >Film<br><td bgcolor=white >Kin-dza-dza, Mimino.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>RUS</b> 1900-1955<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=370'>Dunayevsky, Isaak<br><td bgcolor=white >Film<br><td bgcolor=white >Operetta, balet, plays and film comedies, songs. Popular melodies of USSR.<br></tr><tr><td bgcolor=white align=center><b>RUS</b> 1937-<br><td bgcolor=white ><a href='../../classclass/am.php?c_id=371'>Artemyev, Eduard<br><td bgcolor=white >Film electronic<br><td bgcolor=white >Pioneer of electronic music. Combines academic music with rock-culture and electronic music. Combines different styles.<br></tr></table><p>Most known composers are highlighted green